1. Review: normalized gradient descent¶

  • Normalized gradient descent steps of a single input function look like the following
\begin{equation} w^k = w^{k-1} - \alpha \frac{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)}{\sqrt{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)^2}}. \end{equation}

  • Yes, here the denominator is written somewhat redundantly: we could write it more simply as $\sqrt{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)^2} = \left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)\right|$ and $\frac{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)}{\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)\right|} = \text{sign}\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)\right)$

  • So we could write our normalized step as

\begin{equation} w^k = w^{k-1} - \alpha \, \text{sign}\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)\right). \end{equation}
  • In any case, this helps gradient descent make progress on flat regions of a single input function - e.g., flat regions leading to a global minimum or saddle points.
  • This is because we normalize out the magnitude of the derivative $\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)$ in doing this, leaving only the direction left to travel in
  • In particular notice that at each step our negative gradient direction has unit length
\begin{equation} \left\Vert\frac{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)}{\sqrt{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right)^2}}\right\Vert_2 = 1 \end{equation}

  • So we always move a distance = $\alpha\,\,\,\,\,$ (our steplenght / learning rate)

  • Practically speaking then: in flat regions where $\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w^{k-1}\right) \approx 0$ we still move in the direction of the negative derivative, with a distance = $\alpha$

  • So if even if $\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w\right)$ is small $\left\Vert\frac{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w\right)}{\sqrt{\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}w}g\left(w \right)^2}}\right\Vert_2 = 1$

  • For multi-input functions this normalized gradient descent step looks like
\begin{equation} \mathbf{w}^k = \mathbf{w}^{k-1} - \alpha \frac{\nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)}{\left\Vert \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right) \right\Vert_2 } \end{equation}
  • This also helps push gradient descent through flat regions of a cost surface since the normalization counter-acts the fact that the entire gradient vanishes in these sorts of regions.
  • Like its single-input analog, this can in particular help push gradient descent through saddle points, where the gradient value nears zero $ \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right) \approx \mathbf{0}$.

2. Component-wise normalized gradient descent¶

  • However note that - in terms of how they are normalized - this kind of normalization treats all of the partial derivative directions equally.
  • That is, they are all normalized using the same constant = $\left\Vert \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right) \right\Vert_2$, which includes in it the length of every partial derivative since
\begin{equation} \left\Vert \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}\right) \right\Vert_2 = \sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^N \left(\frac{\partial}{\partial w_n}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)\right)^2}. \end{equation}
  • So the $j^{th}$ partial derivative is normalized as
\begin{equation} \frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)}{\left\Vert \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}\right) \right\Vert_2} = \frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)}{\sqrt{\sum_{n=1}^N \frac{\partial}{\partial w_n}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)^2}} \end{equation}
  • In doing this we are not always replicating the kind of fix we saw in the single-input case along each partial derivative direction
  • This can be less than ideal if only some of our partial derivatives are vanishing along a run, i.e., we are at a flat region of a cost function with respect to only some of our weights, which will still hold up progress of gradient descent
  • Say for example that we are on a flat region of a cost for only the $j^{th}$ weight $w_j$ of a multi-input function, then the $j^{th}$ partial derivative is vanishing $\left\Vert\frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)}{\left\Vert \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}\right) \right\Vert_2}\right\Vert_2 \ll 1$.
    • In this sense the simple normalized gradient descent scheme above is a rather blunt tool for multi-input functions - if only a few partial derivatives are vanishing it does not help us overcome flat regions of a cost
  • Instead of normalizing each partial derivative by the length of the entire gradient, we can normalize each partial derivative with respect to only itself and avoid this issue
  • that is in the $j^{th}$ weight we normalize the corresponding partial derivative as
\begin{equation} \frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)}{\sqrt{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)^2}} = \frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)}{\left|\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j} g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)\right|} = \text{sign}\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)\right) \end{equation}
  • So in the $j^{th}$ direction we can write our step as (a generalization of our original simple normalization scheme for single-input functions)
\begin{equation} w_j^k = w_j^{k-1} - \alpha \, \text{sign}\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}\right)\right). \end{equation}
  • The entire component-wise normalized step can be similarly written as
\begin{equation} \mathbf{w}^k = \mathbf{w}^{k-1} - \alpha \, \text{sign}\left(\nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)\right) \end{equation}
  • This can likewise be considered a global normalized version of gradient descent with respect to the $\ell_{\infty}$ norm (see Section 13.8)
  • Another way to think about it - dividing off the length of each partial derivative is equivalent to adjusting the steplength / learning rate along each coordinate direction according to the magnitude of each partial derivative
  • We can see this by just rewriting the step for the $j^{th}$ input - moving the denominator over to sit under the steplength / learning rate parameter $\alpha$
\begin{equation} w_j^k = w_j^{k-1} - \left[\frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)^2}}\right] \frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right). \end{equation}
  • We are scaling the steplength $\alpha \longleftarrow \frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)^2}}$ along each coordinate direction independently, and at each update step here!
  • The smaller the length of the partial derivative $\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)$ the larger we adjust its individual steplength
  • This is commonly a much more useful normalized gradient descent step than the original for MLPs, since they have many parameters and flat areas all over the place in subsets of them

def gradient_descent(g,w,alpha,max_its,version):    
    # flatten the input function, create gradient based on flat function
    g_flat, unflatten, w = flatten_func(g, w)
    grad = compute_grad(g_flat)

    # record history
    w_hist = []
    w_hist.append(unflatten(w))

    # start gradient descent loop
    z = np.zeros((np.shape(w)))      # momentum term
    
    # over the line
    for k in range(max_its):   
        # plug in value into func and derivative
        grad_eval = grad(w)
        grad_eval.shape = np.shape(w)

        ### normalized or unnormalized descent step? ###
        if version == 'normalized':
            grad_norm = np.linalg.norm(grad_eval)
            if grad_norm == 0:
                grad_norm += 10**-6*np.sign(2*np.random.rand(1) - 1)
            grad_eval /= grad_norm
            
        if version == 'component_normalized':
            component_norm = np.abs(grad_eval)
            ind = np.argwhere(component_norm < 10**(-6))
            component_norm[ind] = 10**(-6)
            grad_eval /= component_norm
            
        # take descent step with momentum
        z = beta*z + grad_eval
        w = w - alpha*z

        # record weight update
        w_hist.append(unflatten(w))

    return w_hist

3. Mean-normalized gradient descent schemes¶

  • We have now seen how normalized, and component-normalized, gradient descent help us ameliorate a fundamental deficiency of the gradient (in terms of how it can be used as a descent direction in any local optimization scheme): that the gradient vanishes at flat regions of a function
  • The other fundamental problem with the gradient as search direction: zig-zagging
  • How do we deal with zig-zagging? Lots of ways e.g., momentum
  • However in the context of dynamic systems, the notion of averaging (and in particular exponential-averaging) is another key idea
  • The standard gradient descent scheme is an order $\mathcal{O} = 1$ dynamic system. In other words, it doesn't have much memory. This is why standard gradient descent tends to zig-zag along long narrow valleys of a cost function.
  • The way we traditionally write our gradient descent step $\mathbf{w}^k = \mathbf{w}^{k-1} - \alpha \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)$ tells us that the step $\mathbf{w}^{k}$ is dependent on its immediate predecessor $\mathbf{w}^{k-1}$. Our sequence written out one update at a time clearly - in the context of time series - shows itself to be a fixed order dynamic system.
\begin{equation} \mathbf{w}^1 = \mathbf{w}^{0} - \alpha \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{0}\right) \\ \mathbf{w}^2 = \mathbf{w}^{1} - \alpha \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{1}\right) \\ \vdots \\ \mathbf{w}^k = \mathbf{w}^{k-1} - \alpha \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right) \\ \vdots \end{equation}
  • In terms of dynamic systems / memory / etc., when we add a momentum term to our gradient descent step - something we do explicitly to try to avoid zig-zagging with a gradient method - we increase the order of its memory by one.
  • In other words, the momentum step (introduced in Section 13.4) then 'adds more memory' to the gradient descent step, making $\mathbf{w}^{k}$ dependent on its previous $\mathcal{O} = 2$ predecessors via the update step
\begin{equation} \mathbf{w}^k = \mathbf{w}^{k-1} - \alpha \nabla g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right) + \beta\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1} - \mathbf{w}^{k-2}\right). \end{equation}
  • So it too is a fixed order dynamic system, just one of slightly larger order.
  • Avoiding zig-zagging = smoothing: what other kind of dynamic systems model do we know that tend to smooth time series?
  • Moving averages / exponential averages
  • What shall we average - the weight update or the gradient? Both are zig-zagging.
  • Since the gradient determines each update it makes sense to average it
  • Many ways one could think to do this
  • When combined with a (coordinate) normalized descent direction $\mathbf{d}^{k}$ this sort of algorithm helps ameliorate both of the gradient's natural problems (insofar as it is used as a descent direction)
  • That is, if we keep a (componentwise) normalization scheme we help our algortihm blast through flat portions of a function, and if we then average these normalization factors we can also help ameliorate zig-zagging
  • So we will replace in our componentwise normalized gradient descent scheme each partial derivative magnitude with an averaged version
  • A large number of popular gradient methods employ this sort of procedure - including RMSprop, AdaGrad, AdaDelta,...
  • Most popular methods average the component-wise normalization - i.e., the magnitude of each partial derivative - replacing it with some sort of moving / exponential average of its past
  • In the case of an exponential average, let $h_j^{k}$ denotes the exponential average of of the squared magnitude of the $j^{th}$ partial derivative at step $k$
\begin{equation} h_j^k = \gamma \, h_j^{k-1} + \left(1 - \gamma\right)\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)\right)^2 \end{equation}
  • A gradient descent method that moves according a negative gradient with exponentially normalized partial derivatives then consists of two steps per update: 1) updating the exponential average of each partial derivative magnitude and 2) moving in this direction
\begin{equation} h_j^k = \gamma \, h_j^{k-1} + \left(1 - \gamma\right)\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)\right)^2 \\ w_j^k = w_j^{k-1} - \alpha \frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j} g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)}{\sqrt{h_j^{k-1}}} \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, \end{equation}
  • This is often called RMSprop (Root Mean Squared Propogation) - and again many other popular first order methods (e.g., Adam, AdaDelta, etc.,) are quite similar
  • As with the standard normalized methods, in practice a small nonnegative $\epsilon > 0$ is typcally added to the denominator of the second line to avoid dividing by zero
\begin{equation} h_j^k = \gamma \, h_j^{k-1} + \left(1 - \gamma\right)\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j}g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)\right)^2 \\ w_j^k = w_j^{k-1} - \alpha \frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial w_j} g\left(\mathbf{w}^{k-1}\right)}{\sqrt{h_j^{k-1}}+ \epsilon} \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, \end{equation}

Example. Exponential normalized gradient descent - a.k.a. RMSprop¶

In [29]:
def RMSprop(g,w,alpha,max_its,**kwargs):        
    # rmsprop params
    gamma=0.9
    eps=10**-8
    if 'gamma' in kwargs:
        gamma = kwargs['gamma']
    if 'eps' in kwargs:
        eps = kwargs['eps']
    
    # flatten the input function, create gradient based on flat function
    g_flat, unflatten, w = flatten_func(g, w)
    grad = compute_grad(g_flat)

    # initialize average gradient
    avg_sq_grad = np.ones(np.size(w))
    
    # record history
    w_hist = [unflatten(w)]

    # over the line
    for k in range(max_its):                           
        # evaluate and shape grad
        grad_eval = grad(w)
        grad_eval.shape = np.shape(w)
        
        # update exponential average of past gradients
        avg_sq_grad = gamma*avg_sq_grad + (1 - gamma)*grad_eval**2 
    
        # take descent step 
        w = w - alpha*grad_eval / (avg_sq_grad**(0.5) + eps)

        # record weight update, train and val costs
        w_hist.append(unflatten(w))

    return w_hist

activation = 'tanh'
layer_sizes = [1,3,3,1]
feats = nonlib.multilayer_perceptron.Setup(activation = activation,layer_sizes = layer_sizes)
feature_transforms = feats.feature_transforms
initializer = feats.initializer

# parameters for our two runs of gradient descent
scale = 0.1
w = np.array([scale*np.random.randn(2,1),scale*np.random.randn(2,1)])

w = initializer()
max_its = 1500; alpha_choice = 10**(-2)

# run on original data
run0 = nonlib.basic_runner.Setup(x,y,feature_transforms,normalize = 'None')
run0.fit(w=w,alpha_choice = alpha_choice,max_its=max_its)

# run on original data
run1 = nonlib.basic_runner.Setup(x,y,feature_transforms,normalize = 'None',version = 'component_normalized')
run1.fit(w=w,alpha_choice = alpha_choice,max_its=max_its)

# run on original data
run2 = nonlib.basic_runner.Setup(x,y,feature_transforms,normalize = 'None',algo = 'RMSprop')
run2.fit(w=w,alpha_choice = alpha_choice,max_its=max_its,gamma = 0.9)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def show_series(series):
    series = np.abs(np.array(series).T)
    num_parts,num_samples = series.shape
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (9,6))
    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    a,b = np.meshgrid(np.arange(num_samples),np.arange(num_parts))

    ### x-axis Customize minor tick labels ###
    # make custom labels
    x_ticker_range = np.arange(0.5,num_samples,1).tolist()
    x_char_range = np.arange(num_samples)
    y_ticker_range = np.arange(0.5,num_parts,1).tolist()
    y_char_range = np.arange(num_parts)

    ax.xaxis.tick_top()

    ## assign major or minor ticklabels? - chosen major by default
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.FixedLocator(x_ticker_range))
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FixedFormatter(x_char_range))

    ### y-axis Customize minor tick labels ###
    # make custom labels
    y_ticker_range = np.arange(0.5,num_parts,1).tolist()

    ## assign major or minor ticklabels? - chosen major by default
    ax.yaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.FixedLocator(y_ticker_range))
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FixedFormatter(y_char_range))
    
    cdict = {
  'red'  :  ( (0.0, 0.25, .25), (0.02, .59, .59), (1., 1., 1.)),
  'green':  ( (0.0, 0.0, 0.0), (0.02, .45, .45), (1., .97, .97)),
  'blue' :  ( (0.0, 1.0, 1.0), (0.02, .75, .75), (1., 0.8, 0.45))
    }
    
    ax.pcolormesh(a, b, -series,cmap = 'hot',edgecolor = 'k') # hot, gist_heat, cubehelix
